As with anything, hoping for a solution by not reading the manual is a stupid idea and a waste of everyone's time when you criticise the framework for your lack of knowledge.  There is no inconsistency as you mention, the same applies to the framework knowing what new html you want to put in the dialog.  It doesn't auto-magically know you want to replace html.  **You** tell it to by a method just the same as **you** have to with firing the `create` event.  The reason that these events don't auto-fire on every single DOM manipulation is that the computational overhead is relatively expensive, particularly on a mobile device and hence the developer can decide when he/she is done augmenting the DOM and when it's best to trigger the `create` event.  So if you are concious enough to have added in HTML dynamically, you should be concious enough to trigger the `create` event at a time which is most suitable.

The very reason that the codebase does this is to make applications built on the framework better for the end-user.  Hence I can't see this being a valid feature request as it would slow down the responsiveness of the framework for everyone else, all the time, when all it needs is for developers to read the manual!

