@grandecomplex - Thanks for the encouragement. We already approach this in a layered way, though a bit different than you. On toolbars, we're moving away from the dynamic re-positioning completely because they tend to scroll with the page due to way mobile browsers "freeze" the display during scrolls and we figure it's cleaner looking to fall back to them scrolling with the page. We use position:fixed for platforms like iOS5, Android 2.2+, Playbook, BB7, Kindle Fire, etc. because it is so lightweight and allows each platform to use native scrolling which will feel "right". 

Using overflow:auto on iOS is almost awesome but we rand into a lot fo issues when we used this for our touchOverfow feature (now deprecated for 1.1). There were a few bugs: content wouldn't render randomly inside a scrolled container, forcing us to apply a transform to force rendering which introduces lots of off CSS flakiness; tapping the clock to scroll to top didn't work (in fact it crashed the browser a lot); and the scrolling momentum is different than normal pages. Overflow is still a good feature and we're looking at re-using a lot of this work for handling overflow regions for tablets but it seemed to introduce too many bugs to add to every page just to smooth out transitions and get fixed headers (we worked out other solutions to these issues).

Anyway, all good stuff and feel free to help us out by commenting or providing fixes via pull requests.

