@mathiaslin 

When the pageinit event fires, that just signals that the framework is done enhancing the page. It does _NOT_ mean that the browser has responded to the changes we just made to the DOM/CSS. Changes to the DOM/CSS usually generate layout requests, but most browsers batch them for performance reasons, and don't actually re-layout the document until the call-stack unwinds and the app returns to the main-event loop. This is why setTimeout() magically fixes things for folks. When the timeout fires, the browser has had time to re-layout the document so that the height of the document is accurate, and most importantly larger than the viewport size, which is a requirement for the navbar to be scrolled off screen.

That all said, there are certain properties that you can access, that the browser can't give you an answer for unless it does a synchronous layout. If you access properties like offsetWidth/offsetHeight/scrollWidth/scrollHeight on something like the body element, that is usually enough to cause the browser to go through the layout motions immediately, so use with care.

